argin:0;">The battle for control of the 119th Congress, which was already a=
bout as tight and
evenly divided as any Congress <em>ever</em>, became just a little more com=
plicated this week, straining <strong>Mike Johnson</strong>=E2=80=99s three=
-vote margin and creating new headaches for whips on both sides of the aisl=
e. Yesterday, the House honored Houston Democratic Rep. <strong>Sylvester T=
urner</strong>, who died on Wednesday from =E2=80=9Cenduring health complic=
ations,=E2=80=9D according to a family statement=E2=80=94less than a year a=
fter the death of his predecessor in the 18th District, <strong>Sheila Jack=
son
Lee</strong>, who passed away from pancreatic cancer. A 70-year-old freshma=
n, Turner ended up serving only 62 days in the House.<br/><br/>With Turner=
=E2=80=99s passing, there are now three official House vacancies: the Houst=
on seat; Florida=E2=80=99s 1st, previously held by Republican <strong>Matt =
Gaetz</strong>, who resigned; and Florida=E2=80=99s 6th, which <strong>Mike=
 Waltz</strong> abdicated to serve as Trump=E2=80=99s national security adv=
isor. All three are safely ensconced in highly partisan geographies, and ar=
e not
expected to change parties, but they will be closely watched. Nevertheless,=
 there=E2=80=99s a possibility that Republican Gov. <strong>Greg Abbott</st=
rong> will keep Turner=E2=80=99s seat open until November, <a href=3D"https=
://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWYmhBaGYx=
